'''Shimotsukeno no Mushimaro''' (下毛野 虫麻呂, dates unknown) was a [[Nara period]] noble and [[literary figure]]. His [[kabane|clan name]] was [[Asomi]]. He was likely a close relative of {{ill|Shimotsukeno no Komaro|ja|下毛野古麻呂|12=draft|12=draft}}, a [[Sangi|councilor]]. His rank was {{ill|Senior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|ja||ja|従五位上|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|12=draft|12=draft}}, and he held the post of {{ill|Junior Assistant Minister of the Ministry of Ceremonies|ja|式部員外少輔|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Career == In [[Yōrō 4]] (720), Mushimaro was appointed to the rank of {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|ja||ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|12=draft|12=draft}}. The following year, in [[Yōrō 5]] (721), he was promoted to {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|ja||ja|従五位上|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|12=draft|12=draft}} along with {{ill|Goso Kumohime|ja|呉粛胡明|12=draft|12=draft}}. During the same month, {{ill|Empress Genshō|ja|元正天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} rewarded officials who demonstrated exceptional academic ability, and Mushimaro was recognized for his literary excellence. He, along with {{ill|Yamada Mikata|ja|山田三方|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ki Kiyohito|ja|紀清人|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Takao no Kawachi|ja|楽浪河内|12=draft|12=draft}}, received 15 bolts of silk, 15 skeins of [[silk thread]], 30 rolls of [[hemp cloth]], and 20 iron hoes. In June of the same year, he was appointed {{ill|Junior Assistant Minister of the Ministry of Ceremonies|ja|式部員外少輔|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Mushimaro’s works include two policy responses compiled in the ''{{ill|Keikokushū|ja|経国集|12=draft|12=draft}}''. Additionally, a five-line regulated verse poem (律詩) written during a banquet at {{ill|Prince Nagaya's residence|ja|長屋王邸|12=draft|12=draft}} to bid farewell to guests from {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|12=draft|12=draft}} was included in the ''{{ill|Kaifūsō|ja|懐風藻|12=draft|12=draft}}'' along with its preface. According to the ''Kaifūsō'' index, his rank at the time was Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade, and he served as a university lecturer (大学助教). He is believed to have passed away at the age of 36.
== Official Positions == Details are primarily from the ''{{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|12=draft|12=draft}}'' unless otherwise noted: * Date unknown: {{ill|Senior Sixth Rank|lt=Senior Sixth Rank, Upper Grade|ja|正六位上|1=Senior Sixth Rank|lt=Senior Sixth Rank, Upper Grade|12=draft|12=draft}} * [[Yōrō 4]] (720), 11th month, 11th day: {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|12=draft|12=draft}}. Autumn: Appointed {{ill|Lecturer at the Imperial University|ja|大学助教|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>''Kaifūsō''</ref> * [[Yōrō 5]] (721), 1st month, 5th day: {{ill|Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|ja|従五位上|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|12=draft|12=draft}}. 1st month, 27th day: Received silk, silk thread, hemp cloth, and hoes. 6th month, 26th day: Appointed {{ill|Junior Assistant Minister of the Ministry of Ceremonies|ja|式部員外少輔|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Notes == {{footnotes}}<references /> == References == * ''Shoku Nihongi 2'' (Shin Nihon Koten Bungaku Taikei 13), [[Iwanami Shoten]], 1990. * {{ill|Ujitani Mitsuru|ja|宇治谷孟|12=draft|12=draft}}, ''Shoku Nihongi (Volume 1)'', [[Kodansha]] (Kodansha Gakujutsu Bunko), 1992, ISBN 4061590308. * {{ill|Eguchi Takao|ja|江口孝夫|12=draft|12=draft}}, ''Complete Commentary on Kaifūsō'', Kodansha (Kodansha Gakujutsu Bunko), 2000. * {{ill|Sakamoto Tarō|ja|坂本太郎|12=draft|12=draft}}, edited by {{ill|Hirano Kunio|ja|平野邦雄|12=draft|12=draft}}, ''Dictionary of Japanese Ancient Clan Names'', [[Yoshikawa Kōbunkan]], 1990, ISBN 4642022430.
